DOCUMENT();
############################################################ # Load Macros ############################################################ loadMacros( "PGstandard.pl", "PGML.pl", "AnswerFormatHelp.pl", "PCCmacros.pl", "parserNumberWithUnits.pl", "parserLinearRelation.pl", "PGcourse.pl", ); COMMENT('Authored in PreTeXt');
############################################################ # Header ############################################################ TEXT(beginproblem());
############################################################ # PG Setup Code ############################################################ $rate = random(1,3,0.1); $speed = NumberWithUnits("$rate psi/min"); $initial = random(20,25); $start = NumberWithUnits("$initial psi"); $final = random(30,34); $end = NumberWithUnits("$final psi"); Context("LinearRelation")->variables->are(t => 'Real'); $equation = LinearRelation("$initial + $rate t = $final");
############################################################ # Body ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML Write an equation to model the scenario. There is no need to solve the equation.
One of the tires on your car looks a little flat. You measure its air pressure and are alarmed to see it so low at [`[$start]\text{.}`] You have a portable device that can pump air into the tire increasing the pressure at a rate of [`[$speed]\text{.}`] How long will it take to fill the tire to the manual's recommended pressure of [`[$end]\text{?}`] Write an equation to model this scenario. There is no need to solve it.
[@KeyboardInstructions('Use [|t|]* as the variable.')@]**
[_]{$equation}{20}
END_PGML
############################################################ # Solution ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION This is a rate exercise, and we can use
[``` (\text{initial value}) \pm (\text{rate})\cdot\text{variable} = (\text{final value}) ```]
In this case, the initial value for the pressure is [`[$initial]\text{,}`] the pressure is increasing (so we will add, not subtract), the rate is [`[$rate]\text{,}`] and the final pressure value is [`[$final]\text{.}`] The one thing we do not know is how much time it will take to fill the tire, so we decide to use [`t`] to represent that time. So the equation to set up is:
[``` [$equation] ```]
END_PGML_SOLUTION
